time to reach the colony.  Even three months is a long time to send<br>
reinforcements.  Think of colonial America revolting against the much <br>
more powerful England.  Granted the former received help from the <br>
french but I think the analogy still holds. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2621<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/29/02 5:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=512.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Can't We Just Stop Getting Along?</span><hr size=1> Governments just don't have any interest in space. They look at immediate gain investments. Their leader decides on the direction of resources. He has a term lasting a few short years. He wants to be remembered and supported by the people in the next election so he might get a second term. Space travel is a money pit which wont show big returns until after he is out of office. He wants to show a victory of some kind to the people within a couple of years. Increased holiday pay, a war on some small nation, a new trade agreement, decreased unemployment. Space promises nothing short term. I doubt many politicians have even considered the possible future ramifications of public access to Space. <br>
<br>
It is amazing how the whole world ignores nuclear rocketry. Sometimes I wonder how this reality can possibly be real. I mean, how can so many people be blind to the most incredible opportunity facing us. It is almost like a conspiracy to keep space free of civilians. I wonder what it must be like to really look down on the Earth from deep space. Can you imagine the sense freedom? The Earth and everything you know is a little blue ball hanging in front of your window. The solar system is yours to travel. It would be nice to have the option of travelling into space available. It really would. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 495<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/29/02 9:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=512.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Can't We Just Stop Getting Along?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Wait, there's something I don't understand. Even if a nation aggressively pursued an idea like Orion or Mauk2's Liberty Ship, it would take many decades for a significant population to inhabit space. I don't think any government would have to worry about space colonists to revolt, there would simply be too few to govern an independent state, I think. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It doesn't take long for a sizable population to grow if a fair number of colonists (say 50 males, 50 females) have children.  Population growth occurs along an exponential curve.  I believe there won't be mass migrations from Earth but rather it will be the descendents of the relatively few people who do leave Earth who ultimately populate space.  But in any case there just isn't a huge incentive for governments to build the infrastructure that would support any sizable population in space.  I imagine most government funded &quot;colonies&quot; would strictly rotate people in and out to keep the population at a predetermined level.  It just makes sense to do that for a number of reasons both political and practical.  I firmly believe it'll be private parties that ultimately settle space &quot;big time.&quot;  Maybe not for a hundred years, but eventually. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A> at: 11/29/02 9:31:07 pm<br></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showPrevMessage?topicID=512.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showNextMessage?topicID=512.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=512.topic&index=9><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/addreply3.jpg border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.emailToFriend?topicID=512.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.threadControl?topicID=512.topic><img 